REQUIREMENTS - You will need the following mods:

  • ComfySigns
  • SnapPointsMadeEasy
  • FenceSnap
  • ComfyGizmo

Some important things to keep in mind.

  • REMEMBER TO TAKE BREAKS! This tool makes it very easy to get in a rhythm and just place sign after sign, which can easily trigger Repetitive Stress Injuries or Arthritis, so don't push yourself too hard. It's not a race ♥
  • The width of your image will directly impact the number of columns you'll need for your image.
  • If you have a picture that's just slightly too tall and it ends up "oversized", then try reducing the size in a photo editor or if you want it to be bigger, you can split it in half horizontally, and output the sign as "5 per columns". If you chose to do this, you'll need to adjust the Y accordingly so that both halves will match properly.
  • The final instance count will be at least the sign count. So if your project uses 400 signs, it'll be 400 instances assuming you remove all the support material.
  • Transport costs with the Creator Shop are relatively cheap for signs due to how thin the project is. If you don't feel comfortable digging into the ground to build there, you can build it above ground and pay with blue mushrooms to have it transported under the ground for you.

Help! How do I use this tool?

There's some setup you'll need to do in order to use the code from this tool. You'll need a building hammer, wood and charcoal. You will also likely want colorfulPieces (for keeping track of which sign you're currently on), Fence Snap (Required for snapping Signs to the fence poles)Snap Points Made Easy (Required for placing the fence posts that we'll use for creating the structure array), and ComfyGizmo (Which makes rotations easier but it's not required for this tool to work). I also recommend using torches and/or just ensuring you're in a well lit area. Also, setting the wall behind your final image to be black or white may make it more visible.

Make sure to configure Snap Points Made easy so that you can toggle the snap points. You'll want to be set to "Switched to Closest" for this project

You'll want to start by placing 6x 1m (small) wooden beams up, so that you have a pillar (if you're building into the ground, you'll need to dig out the space and then place your pillars down in a line, the rest of the process will remain the same).

Then, you'll need to locate the Roundpole Fence item in your build hammer. You will want to rotate this item so that the 4 fence bars are facing towards you in a horizontal way. The fence should be on it's side and you want to snap it to the side of the fence. Place 10 of these along the edge of your pillar.

Then place fences attached to those first fences to create a continuous line. You'll need to overlap the poles slightly for each connecting fence post in order to be able to place all your signs in a row with no gaps

The resulting array will be something like this:

Now you're ready to place your first sign! Simply click your first sign into the highest and farthest left most fencepole that you can click onto. I recommend placing signs for the entire column (so 5 or 10 depending on your sign). Then, simply click on the button with the number "1", edit the sign in game, and paste the text from your clipboard into the sign. The button automatically copies the text for you, so it'll be as easy as placing, clicking the button, and pasting into the sign. Then just continue the process until you've completed that column.

Once you finish your first column, simply repeat the process of placing your next column of signs. I recommmend coloring every other sign so that you have a checkerboard pattern. It makes it easier to keep track of how many columns you've completed so far, visually speaking.

You'll start to see your image appear in real-time above your array. You may need to play around with the x and y settings in order to have it land in the correct location for your art work.

Now you're ready to make your first sign.

Here's a pro tip, Make sure to start with something small; you'll get more detail out of it than you think at first, and the larger your project, the more signs you may need.

Welcome to the ComfyValheim Sign Generator

This is a free tool provided for the ComfyValheim community but (other use cases are welcome).

Max image size: 2000 x 2000 pixels*.
Keep in mind that most images above 300px in height will be considered "oversized" and the resulting size code will not fit the 999 character sign limit for ComfyValheim.
Larger images will be rejected to ensure stability and performance.
Please be respectful with the content you upload — other players will see these signs in-game, and excessive detail will increase the instance load for others during rendering.

For questions or support, reach out to @EnjeruTantei on Discord.
